[[File:Apple trees at Fishkill Farms.jpg|thumb|Apple trees ready for U-pick harvesting at Fishkill Farms]]
'''Fishkill Farms''' is an [[apple]] [[orchard]] and small-scale farm located in [[Hopewell Junction]], a hamlet of [[East Fishkill]] in [[Dutchess County, New York]]. Founded by family friends of President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], Fishkill Farms is one of the [[Hudson Valley]]'s oldest apple orchards.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url = http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2015/07/28/dateline-morgenthau-family-homestead-fishkill-farms-local-history/30812361/|title = 102 years later, Fishkill Farms still in care of Morgenthau family|date = July 28, 2015|accessdate = October 14, 2015|website = Poughkeepsie Journal|publisher = Poughkeepsie Journal|last = Musso|first = Anthony p.}}</ref> Organic Authority LLC named Fishkill Farms its 2010 "top pick" apple farm in the [[New York metropolitan area|New York City]] area.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Big Apple – Top 5 apple picking farms near NYC - Organic Authority|url = http://www.organicauthority.com/foodie-buzz/the-big-apple-top-5-apple-picking-farms-near-nyc.html|website = Organic Authority|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref>

== History ==
Fishkill Farms was founded by U.S. Secretary of the Treasury [[Henry Morgenthau, Jr.]], who purchased the land in 1914. The farm has been handed down through family members, including former Manhattan District Attorney [[Robert M. Morgenthau]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|title = The Manhattan Morgenthaus Are Farmers, Too|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303595404579318903949156422|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|access-date = 2015-10-14|issn = 0099-9660|first = Ralph Gardner|last = Jr}}</ref> The farm is now run by his son, Joshua Morgenthau.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title = Josh Morgenthau takes over family pastime|url = http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2014/10/10/young-professional-fishkill-farms/17057577/|website = The Poughkeepsie Journal|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref>

The farm originally produced apples, chickens and dairy but  ceased dairy farming during [[World War II]] when hired help was hard to find.<ref name=":2" /> In 1980, a hailstorm damaged the apples and rendered them unsellable to wholesale distributors so  the orchard was opened up to the local public for [[pick-your-own|U-pick]] harvesting. The farm has been doing U-pick ever since.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blog.williams-sonoma.com/the-story-of-fishkill-farms/|title = The Story of Fishkill Farms|date = July 27, 2015|accessdate = October 14, 2015|website = Williams-Sonoma Taste|publisher = Williams-Sonoma, Inc.|last = |first = }}</ref>[[File:JoshMorgenthau.JPG|thumb|Josh Morgenthau leads students on a tour of Fishkill Farms]]

== Services ==
Fishkill Farms' 130 acre<ref name=":0" /> property offers U-pick services for produce including blueberries, blackberries, cherries, peaches, nectarines, pears and vegetables.<ref>{{cite web|title = Where to Pick-Your-Own-Berries and Berry-Picking Farms|url = http://www.hvmag.com/Hudson-Valley-Magazine/May-2013/Where-to-Pick-Your-Own-Berries-and-Berry-Picking-Farms/|website = Hvmag.com|publisher = Today Media|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> Pasture-raised hens also produce eggs for the farm.<ref name=":1" /> It also sells produce   in Brooklyn farmers markets and  an order-fulfillment service called Good Eggs.<ref name=":0" /> The farm offers [[community-supported agriculture]] shares for Hudson Valley residents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fishkill Farms|url=http://www.justfood.org/farm/fishkill-farms|website=Justfood.org|publisher=Just Food|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref> Numerous events such as weddings and private affairs are hosted on site, including a recent Autumn Orchard Dinner which was reported upon by the gourmet aficionado [[Williams-Sonoma]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the Guests of Fishkill Farms’ Autumn Orchard Dinner|url = http://blog.williams-sonoma.com/meet-the-guests-fishkill-farms-apple-orchards-dinner/|website = Williams-Sonoma Taste|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref>

== Sustainability ==
[[File:Apple with Ladybug.JPG|thumb|An apple from one of Fishkill's historic orchards]]Farming practices at Fishkill operate with the goal of sustainability and carbon neutrality in mind., with an effort to grow as many foods as possible organically.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fishkill Farms - Red Tomato|url = http://www.redtomato.org/farmers/fishkill-farms/|website = Red Tomato|accessdate = 2015-10-15|language = en}}</ref> The farm intend to   consciously select crop varieties which are most suited to the effects of [[climate change]] over the next twenty years.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fishkill Farms — Cornell Institute for Climate Change & Agriculture|url = http://climateinstitute.cals.cornell.edu/2015/07/16/fishkill-farms/|website = climateinstitute.cals.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-15}}</ref>

