{{1r|date=March 2017}}<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:D2B.gif|right|thumb|200px|Official D²B logo]] --> '''D²B''' ('''Domestic Digital Bus''', '''IEC 61030''') is an [[International Electrotechnical Commission|IEC]] standard for a low-speed [[multi-master bus|multi-master]] [[serial communication bus]] for [[home automation]] applications. It was originally developed by [[Philips]] in the 1980s. In 2006 it has been withdrawn by IEC because another standard was proposed, JTC1 SC 83/WG1. There remain many IEC61030-compliant devices, such as some Philips-branded head units and CD changers from car stereos.<ref>{{cite web|title=Car Stereos |url=http://www.onlinecarstereo.com |accessdate=21 April 2013|author=Marjorie M. Oliver}}</ref>
The [[SCART]] connector provides a D²B connection for inter-device communication.
