'''Oscar Eugen Nicolai Pedersen''' (6 November 1857 – 5 March 1913) was a Norwegian industrialist.
He was born in [[Halden|Fredrikshald]]. He attended middle school in Fredrikshald and technical school in [[Horten]], and then studied chemistry at the [[Fachhochschule|Dresden University of Applied Sciences]]. He graduated in 1880, and worked as an engineer and chemist at the Hafslund Chemical Wood Pulp Factory ({{lang-no|Hafslund Kemiske Træmassefabrik}}) from 1883 to 1889. He came in contact with [[Carl Kellner (mystic)|Carl Kellner]], and in 1888 Kellner and [[Edward Partington]] bought the Borregård farm,<ref>http://parareligion.ch/sunrise/kellner.htm</ref> acquired rights in [[Sarp Falls]], and established the Kellner-Partington Paper Pulp Co. Ltd. Pedersen was hired as company manager. The company became [[Borregaard]], which Pedersen developed until his relatively early death.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Oscar Pedersen|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Frank Kiel|last=Jacobsen|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Oscar_Pedersen/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=11 September 2010}}</ref>
He married Swedish citizen Polly Wennberg (1866–1920) in April 1884. He died in March 1913 near [[Holmenkollen]].<ref name=nbl/>
